He betook himself ’ to his country houses, of which he possessed several in the West of Italy, and spent the summer first in one and then in, another. During this period of compulsory leisure, full of anxiety, disappointed in the hopes which the death of Caesar had awakened in him and depressed by sorrow for the degra- dation of his country, Cicero sought and found distraction from politics and relief from gloom and disappointment in literary pursuits.
